<p>We believe this URL may be a paid link, which search engines like Google strictly forbid. Google asks users to report instances of people buying or selling links, and state they will penalize both the buyer and seller of links if they detect the practice. The link directed users to a casino game that is still available in the Play Market:</p>
<p><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/heart-of-vegas-slots.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56345" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/heart-of-vegas-slots.png" alt="" width="423" height="437" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/heart-of-vegas-slots.png 423w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/heart-of-vegas-slots.png?resize=290,300 290w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/heart-of-vegas-slots.png?resize=32,32 32w" sizes="(max-width: 423px) 100vw, 423px" /></a></p>
<p>It&#8217;s worth noting that this app also reports having more than 10 million downloads, and discloses that it may charge up to $359.99 per item for in-app purchases. That&#8217;s a lot of cheddar for virtual coins in a simulated gambling app.</p>
<p><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/heart-details.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56346" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/heart-details.png" alt="" width="298" height="164" /></a></p>
<h3><strong>Case study 3: aggressive pop-ups when web surfing</strong></h3>
<p>Ad fraud is not a platform-specific problem: It is widespread on both the Android and iPhone ecosystem, and it takes many forms, including fake alerts and aggressive &#8220;contest winner&#8221; messages.</p>
<p>For example, while browsing an otherwise normal site,&nbsp; no matter which device you use, an ad call may pop open a new tab in the mobile browser, which redirects to pages that look like these:<a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image14.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-56347" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image14.png" alt="" width="350" height="622" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image14.png 646w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image14.png?resize=169,300 169w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image14.png?resize=576,1024 576w" sizes="(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px" /></a></p>
<p>This &#8220;warning&#8221; message uses a template that embeds specific information about your phone&#8217;s manufacturer and model into the page itself. The text in red contains the description &#8220;Google Nexus 5X&#8221; because that version of the phone was used to browse to the site. The User-Agent string transmitted by the phone&#8217;s browser sends that information to the website, which then throws it back in your face to lend the dire warning credibility. The warning is bogus.</p>
<p>Now, consider this message telling the viewer that they could win a large cash prize.<a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image15.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-56348" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image15.png" alt="" width="350" height="758" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image15.png 532w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image15.png?resize=138,300 138w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image15.png?resize=472,1024 472w" sizes="(max-width: 350px) 100vw, 350px" /></a></p>
<p>These highly deceptive ads employ the use of multiple redirects, which prevents the user from returning to the original website. Scripts may prevent you from doing anything other than closing the tab or the entire browser.</p>
<p>Looking at the network traffic generated when we visited the second site shown above, using Safari on iOS, we have basic information that tells an analyst where the site is hosted, how you got there, and in some cases, where you&#8217;ll end up next. In this case, it&#8217;s being hosted on a bare IP address, serving web content from a non-standard port:</p>
<ul>
<li>IP address: 198.245.72.122:8899</li>
<li>User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (iPhone; …)</li>
<li>Referer: the originated website, hxxp://iphone.popur.com/JiaoCheng/6602.html</li>
<li>&#8220;302&#8221; redirect to: hxxp://track.pdyytc.com/…</li>
</ul>
<p><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image16.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56349" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image16.png" alt="" width="640" height="226" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image16.png 1428w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image16.png?resize=300,106 300w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image16.png?resize=768,272 768w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image16.png?resize=1024,362 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3><strong>Case study 4: Google Play mobile in-app pop-ups &amp; notifications</strong></h3>
<p>Many applications on Google&#8217;s Play Market skirt the edge of what one might consider malicious behavior, and are not really safe or pleasant to use. We&#8217;ve recently reported on networks of <a href="https://news.sophos.com/en-us/2019/02/21/abusive-mobile-adware-aggressively-touts-more-adware/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">apps that engage in aggressive promotion of app downloads</a>, almost to the point where one must question whether the main purpose of the app is to just promote other apps. Some apps show annoying full-screen ads or repeatedly display notifications in the notifications bar. These apps routinely engage in the kinds of deceptive and unfair practices that enrage many people.</p>
<ul>
<li>Constantly pop up ads</li>
<li>Charge users a lot of money in order to remove all ads</li>
<li>Even if you pay, you may still see a lot of ads</li>
</ul>
<p>Here are some reviews and comments from users about some of the apps we looked at that engage in these practices:</p>
<p><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image17.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-56350" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image17.png" alt="" width="642" height="157" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image17.png 609w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image17.png?resize=300,73 300w" sizes="(max-width: 642px) 100vw, 642px" /></a></p>
<p><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image18.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-56351" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image18.png" alt="" width="642" height="204" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image18.png 633w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image18.png?resize=300,95 300w" sizes="(max-width: 642px) 100vw, 642px" /></a><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image19.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56352" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image19.png" alt="" width="629" height="107" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image19.png 629w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image19.png?resize=300,51 300w" sizes="(max-width: 629px) 100vw, 629px" /></a><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image20.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56353" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image20.png" alt="" width="640" height="134" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image20.png 656w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image20.png?resize=300,63 300w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image21.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56354" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image21.png" alt="" width="617" height="82" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image21.png 617w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image21.png?resize=300,40 300w" sizes="(max-width: 617px) 100vw, 617px" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Some apps exhibit ransomware-like behavior. They may:</p>
<ul>
<li>Change the lock screen</li>
<li>Show notification everywhere (inside or outside apps)</li>
<li>Every time open the app, there is an ad</li>
<li>Frequently ask for payment</li>
</ul>
<p>As a researcher, I heard there are some complains about pop-ups exiting sleep mode. I did some research, and here is the conversion between several end users. The user pointed out that the <strong>Z camera</strong> app (from GOMO) may cause the issue. Z camera is a photo editor and &#8220;Beauty Selfie&#8221; app on Google Play.</p>
<p><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image22.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56355" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image22.png" alt="" width="640" height="184" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image22.png 828w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image22.png?resize=300,86 300w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image22.png?resize=768,221 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image23.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56356" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image23.png" alt="" width="640" height="71" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image23.png 827w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image23.png?resize=300,33 300w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image23.png?resize=768,85 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image24.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-56357" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image24.png" alt="" width="640" height="72" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image24.png 831w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image24.png?resize=300,34 300w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image24.png?resize=768,87 768w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a></p>
<p>After digging the decompiled code, here is our finding:</p>
<ul>
<li>the app will cache ad sites once every hour</li>
<li>The app uses the USER_PRESENT permission to launch a full screen ad when the user unlocks their device</li>
</ul>
<figure id="attachment_56358" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-56358" style="width: 529px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image25.png"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-56358 size-full" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image25.png" alt="" width="529" height="234" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image25.png 529w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image25.png?resize=300,133 300w" sizes="(max-width: 529px) 100vw, 529px" /></a><figcaption id="caption-attachment-56358" class="wp-caption-text">Code that triggers a display when the device is unlocked</figcaption></figure>
<figure id="attachment_56359" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-56359" style="width: 640px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image26.png"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-56359 size-full" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image26.png" alt="" width="640" height="51" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image26.png 723w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image26.png?resize=300,24 300w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /></a><figcaption id="caption-attachment-56359" class="wp-caption-text">Code that updates the ads every hour (3.6 million milliseconds)</figcaption></figure>
<p>Let us turn back to the first paragraph that mentioned the Cheetah Mobile app (CM File Manager) and Kika Tech app (Kika Keyboard), which were reportedly <a href="https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/craigsilverman/google-removes-cheetah-kika-apps" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">removed by Google due to the engagement in &#8220;clickfraud&#8221;</a> by claiming credit for app installs. The report was firstly released by an app analytic firm Kochava, and it caused Cheetah&#8217;s stock price to drop 30% on Nov. 27, 2018.</p>
<p><a href="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image27.png"><img loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-56360" src="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image27.png" alt="" width="513" height="335" srcset="https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image27.png 1274w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image27.png?resize=300,196 300w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image27.png?resize=768,502 768w, https://news.sophos.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/image27.png?resize=1024,669 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 513px) 100vw, 513px" /></a></p>
<p>According to <a href="https://www.androidpolice.com/2018/11/28/evidence-points-to-cheetah-mobile-and-kika-tech-engaging-in-massive-click-fraud-scheme/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ryan Whitwam of Android Police</a>, a mobile news website, the problem was endemic.</p>
<blockquote><p>Credit for app installs is yet another advertising model &#8211; one that pushes apps. If you see an ad, you might end up clicking, downloading, and installing that app. Advertisers might pay up to $3 per install when they acquire a new user in this fashion, but claiming that bounty is tricky. When the app is opened for the first time, it does a &#8220;lookback&#8221; to see where the last click originated. The mobile analytics company Kochava claimed Cheetah and Kika were abusing this system using their apps.</p>
<p>In Cheetah’s “click injection” case, the app (a file manager) requires permission to view and open your installed apps, but Cheetah was alleged to watch for any new app installation and submit a fake click, even if they never served the ad to anyone. They also use their permissions to launch apps to ensure they get the bounty.</p>
<p>This affects the advertisers, of course, but legitimate developers could also lose out on a legitimately earned install bounty.</p></blockquote>
<p>Cheetah attempted to blame third-party advertising SDKs or ad networks for this behavior. One of the SDKs can be found in Snaptube app – <strong>Batmobi.</strong></p>
<h2><strong>Conclusion</strong></h2>
<p>In this joint paper, Sophos and Protected Media presented several ad fraud case studies – Snaptube, fastestflashlight, and Z Camera from GOMO, as well CM File Manager or Kika Keyboard.</p>
<p>Although the core products from these companies are different, they have same business model – advertising, just like Google and Facebook. Today, we are unavoidably living in the world of digital advertising. As <a href="https://www.thinkwithgoogle.com/intl/en-145/perspectives/global-articles/building-momentum-against-ad-fraud/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google says</a>, “the digital advertising ecosystem is built on trust, working at its best when all participants are good, and when no one tries to deceive anyone else. That’s why ad fraud is potentially damaging – it can erode trust.”</p>
<p>In the end, everyone is a victim of ad fraud, especially the publishers and advertisers.</p>
<p>Publishers like Google or Facebook should publish more clearer and stricter policy and punish any violation. Companies like Cheetah, Kika Tech,&nbsp; and GOMO should carefully test 3rd party SDKs before adding them into their apps.</p>
<p>These companies should protect their customers rather than leave them to be victimized by ad fraud. Moreover, the entire security industry needs to be collaborative. We need to collaborate and cooperate with government, law enforcement, ad network operators, advertisers, and the users of mobile devices now, and in the future.</p>
<p>Acknowledgments</p>
<p>SophosLabs and threat researcher Rowland Yu gratefully acknowledges the collaboration on this research project with Protected Media and its CTO and cofounder, Dr. Zac Sadan. This research was first presented at the AVAR &#8217;18 conference.</p>
